    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok that makes sense. so basically someone else just holds the money so neither side can grab it until everything is signed? who usually manages the account, like is it a bank or a lawyer?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That's right, the escrow account is a neutral third-party holding account, and it's usually managed by a title company or a lawyer specializing in real estate transactions. They act as the escrow agent, ensuring that the funds are held securely until the closing date. It's a bit like a bank, but instead of depositing your money for you, they hold it on behalf of both you and the seller until the transaction is complete. The title company or lawyer will handle the day-to-day management of the escrow account, making sure that the funds are disbursed according to the terms of the sale.",
